<br>
The list of people on deck for the raid was huge, alas.  There were pages upon pages of sign-ups on the board, and easily around 80 people in zone LFG, punctual and raring to go.<br>
<br>
The raid force was limited to 6 groups to keep it manageable and focused.  My thanks to those to graciously understood the dilemma of headcount, and stayed in touch with me at points through the day to remind me that they stood ready for reinforcement ports as the need arose.  I'm glad that some made it to the raid as we called for replacements, and my apologies to those who did not.  Hopefully we'll see you next time.<br>
<br>
Break-in went very smoothly and by the numbers, with special thanks to Crombattleaxe the Earth Keeper, who kept a steady stream of corpses inbound to camp without training as we ported up 2 groups at a time.<br>
<br>
We were up and ready to begin our battle with spirits high and all players rezzed in the shortest amount of time I've ever seen.<br>
<br>
And then we rocked.<br>
<br>
The raid force cleared the first floor, including 3 clears of the patrol routes.  Maestro of Rancor was slain at SW camp (the raid force pulled the teamwork right out on the fly, and without preamble we slew him as if he were just some Joe Schmuck mob).  His hand was killed as well, although the Very Unpleasant Hand did not pop.<br>
<br>
When the first floor was clear, we took a respite as we refreshed the raid party with some replacements, and pulled down some mobs from the second floor.  Note:  I saw several first floor mobs in the entry hall and houses of the second floor yesterday (why, I have no idea).<br>
<br>
We then went up, and with Kristinlia on lead pull duty, we commenced the battle with second floor mobs, and the raid party advanced to the large entry hall.<br>
<br>
With the area secure, we commenced a roving pillage operation; assailing the second floor mobs at the entries to their own houses.  We had commenced at the middle of the east wall, and worked our way to the southwest corner bringing death when a large part of our raid force had to adjourn for the day.  I estimate that geographically 35 percent of the second floor was clear by the time we adjourned.<br>
<br>
The raid party was a wonderful crew!  My thanks to each and every one of you for your good spirits, your brilliant teamwork, your selflessness, your competence, your willingness to give and receive in a team, and your sense of fun.  I can honestly say that I've never been on a raid of this size with a more pleasant group of people.  The truth is that in any raid, you usually here of one or two who don't gel with the team, or who behave in such a manner as to prompt you to keep an eye on them.  Not so on this raid.  No whiners, no lootwhores, just lots of good team play.  Let's face it, the game is just a game.  The people add the magic.<br>
<br>
Special thanks go to:<br>
* Salenie Mithrilweaver for her brilliant loot management, I know no better loot handler in efficiency and fairness than Salenie.  She has loot managed every Hate raid I have ever been on.<br>
* Crombattleaxe the Earth Keeper for his trademark efficiency and good judgment which resulted in our fast break-in CR, and his excellent job of G4-6 MA<br>
* Siilverain the Wind Caller for her trademark pleasantness and raid management (hey, I'm a monk, sometimes I've gotta camp and clear aggro)<br>
* Boddkin Brandywine for his trademark good spirit and handling of raid-related people issues as they arose.  Take-charge and diplomatic, an excellent combination<br>
* Dirgrin Grymwyrm for a very very very respectable first MA duty in Hate, performing MA duty for G1-3<br>
<br>
Warmest thanks and appreciation to everyone who came along.  You guys created a fun atmosphere and a great day of EQ.<br>
